Running some Metropolis

Here the goal is to find the equilibrium states at different fields. So we run a metropolis algorithm.

To run 1M iterations, it takes about 24-30h, here are the results from the first one.

Which kind of resemble the result from the model Toño made.
But the lines are a bit ugly, so we need to run more simulations to have some statistics. Which is a bummer, since it will take a while. But well, it needs to be done.

New vertices counts

Here the idea is to make vertices counts from the equilibrium plateaus in the 'simstair_detailed' case.

  1. Compute and count the vertices from second half of the plateau
  2. Average in time, this will give me the average counts at a particular field
  3. Do this for all plateaus
    At the end I should have a graph of vertices vs field.

Two things to consider

  • For the staircase_detailed, we don't have data between 0 and 1
  • Actually it was only one xd

With this in mind, we get the following

Which is qualitatively similar, in the sense that the system gets stuck again at low fields, with 2mT being consistent with previous results. Nevertheless, here we notice that dominate the system, followed by lots of type IV defects. Surprisingly only has about 20% of the counts.
For reference here is the comparison. Solid lines are the usual ones, while dotted are the relaxated.

  • Does this mean that we have effects due to making a very quick quenching?
  • Or is it just the result of a different kinetic path that does weird stuff?

Questionably slow quenching

So, we want to know whether we have a effects of rapid quenching. To check this, since in the simulations for the correlations we take around 300s to raise 0.1mT. We discussed to run a quench at a rate of mT/s.

If we consider that approximately 60s in simulation is 1h of computing (yes, it surprised me as well) for a 30x30 system. Then if we go up to 10mT, that needs 30,000s of simulation, which is like 20 days. So we decided to run up to 2mT for a few days to see what happens.
